## Theorem: Laplace of the product between displace unit function and a displaced function{.scrollable}
::: callout-note
## Theorem

:::{#thm-Lpp}

If $F(s)=\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}$ exists for $s>C$ and if $a>0$, then

$$\boxed{\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)f(t-a)\}=e^{-as}\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}=e^{-as}F(s)},\qquad s>C$${#eq-utf}


::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Proof:

$$\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)f(t-a)\}=\int_0^\infty e^{-st} u(t-a)f(t-a)\,dt$$

$$=\int_a^\infty e^{-st} f(t-a)\,dt$$

Change of variables: $$u=t-a\rightarrow u(a)=0$$

$$=\int_0^\infty e^{-s(u+a)} f(u)\,du$$

$$=e^{-sa}\int_0^\infty e^{-su} f(u)\,du$$

$$=e^{-as}F(s)$$
$$=e^{-as}\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}$$
$$\hspace{2in}\square$$

:::
:::
:::


### Example 1 {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-tip}
## Example 

$$\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)\}=?$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution:

$$\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)\}=\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)\cdot (t-a)^0\}$$
$$=e^{-sa}\mathscr{L}\{t^0\}$$
$$=e^{-sa}\frac{1}{s}$$
:::
:::


### Example 2 {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-tip}
## Example 

$$\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)t\}=?$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution:

$$\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)t\}=\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)(t-a)\}+a\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)\}$$

$$=e^{-sa}\mathscr{L}\{t\}+ae^{-sa}\frac{1}{s}$$
$$=e^{-sa}\frac{1}{s^2}+ae^{-sa}\frac{1}{s}$$

:::
:::


### Example 3 {.scrollable}

::: {.callout-tip}
## Example 

Solve: 
$$y''+4y= 0,\qquad 0\leq t< \pi$$
$$y''+4y= \sin t,\qquad t\geq \pi$$

$$y(0)=0, \quad y'(0)=1$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution:

$$y''+4y=u(t-\pi)\sin t$$

$$s^2Y(s)-sy(0)-y'(0)+4Y(s)=\mathscr{L}\{u(t-\pi)\sin t\}$$
We cant use yet @thm-Lpp on the RHS, because $\sin t$ need to be displaced in the same amount of the step function. However we know that $\sin t$ is a periodic function, therefore can be written as: $\sin t = - \sin (t-\pi)$

$$s^2Y(s)-1+4Y(s)=\mathscr{L}\{u(t-\pi)\cdot(-\sin (t-\pi))\}$$
$$s^2Y(s)-1+4Y(s)=-e^{-\pi s}\mathscr{L}\{\sin t\}$$

$$s^2Y(s)-1+4Y(s)=-e^{-\pi s}\frac{1}{s^2+1}$$

$$s^2Y(s)+4Y(s)=\frac{-e^{-\pi s}}{s^2+1}+1$$
$$Y(s)=\frac{-e^{-\pi s}}{(s^2+1)(s^2+4)}+\frac{1}{s^2+4}$$

$$Y(s)=\frac{-e^{-\pi s}+(1+s^2)}{(s^2+1)(s^2+4)}$$

Partial Fractions!:

```{maxima, echo=TRUE}
eqn: (-%e^(-%pi*s)+1+s^2)/((s^2+1)*(s^2+4))$
partfrac(eqn,s);
```


$$Y(s)=\frac{As+B}{s^2+4}+\frac{Cs+D}{s^2+1}$$

$$s^2+(1-e^{-s\pi})=(As+B)(s^2+1)+(Cs+D)(s^2+4)$$
$$s^2+(1-e^{-s\pi})=As^3+As+Bs^2+B+Cs^3+4Cs+Ds^2+4D$$

System of equations from polynomial:

$$0=A+C\rightarrow \boxed{A=-C}$$
$$1=B+D\rightarrow \boxed{B=1-D}$$
$$0=A+4C\rightarrow 3C=0\rightarrow \boxed{C=0,\quad A=0}$$
$$1-e^{-s\pi}=B+4D=(1-D)+4D=1+3D\rightarrow \boxed{D=-\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}} $$
$$\rightarrow \boxed{B=1+\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}}$$

$$Y(s)=\left(1+\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}\right)\frac{1}{s^2+4}-\left(\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}\right)\frac{1}{s^2+1}$$
$$Y(s)=\frac{1}{s^2+4}+\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}\left(\frac{1}{s^2+4}\right)-\left(\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}\right)\frac{1}{s^2+1}$$


Now we can apply the inverse for three terms, first is easy:

$$\mathscr{L}\{\sin(2t)\}=\frac{2}{s^2+4}\Rightarrow \mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s^2+4}\right\}=\frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)$$

and by @eq-utf:

$$e^{-as}\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}=\mathscr{L}\{u(t-a)f(t-a)\}$$, then 

$$\Rightarrow$$

$$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{e^{-\pi s}\frac{1}{s^2+4}\right\}=u(t-\pi)\frac{1}{2}\sin(2(t-\pi))=u(t-\pi)\frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)$$


In the same way:

$$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\left(\frac{e^{-s\pi}}{3}\right)\frac{1}{s^2+1}\right\}=\frac{1}{3}u(t-\pi)\sin(t-\pi)=-\frac{1}{3}u(t-\pi)\sin t$$
Putting all together: $$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{Y(s)\}=\frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)+\frac{1}{6}u(t-\pi)\sin(2t)+\frac{1}{3}u(t-\pi)\sin t$$

$$y(t)=\frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)+\frac{1}{6}u(t-\pi)\sin(2t)+\frac{1}{3}u(t-\pi)\sin t$$
^[you can check in WA here:<https://tinyurl.com/mpzc9un5>]

